Twenty years ago at this exact moment 9AM - I sent the email below from my desk at work, thanking everyone I knew for being part of my life, essentially saying goodbye to them. It was the scariest time of my life. 

I was already in the Marine Corps, as after 9/11, I had left Goldman Sachs to enlist and then finished boot camp at Parris Island. 

I had been at my reserve station with the Marine Corps and we were told that we should go home to get our will and power of attorney together. We were being activated and deployed to Iraq in two days, where we were told there were weapons of mass destruction.

So, twenty years ago this morning, I went to work. I briefly sat at my desk and wrote the email below to everyone that I had known. 

At that point in time in 2003, I had recently moved to Jersey City. I wasn’t registered to vote. I certainly wasn’t elected to office. I was just a person from an immigrant family that felt appreciative for this country and was scared out of his mind for the future.

I will always remember how I felt that day, and it’s hard to believe it has been 20 years. Those types of moments put things in perspective and I’ve been better at not taking anything in life for granted. I'm thankful for my amazing wife, two great children and a City that has embraced me with the opportunity to serve in a special way for multiple terms.

When I think about this note 20 years ago, I would never have imagined that Jersey City would have given me the opportunity of a lifetime nor my path would take me to where I am now. And for that, I wanted to send a note again today to all of you that have been a part of my life over the last 20 year journey in office to say thank you.

Important info in this post below - Domestic Violence and Jersey City- 

It’s already been a tough year w/2 terrible homicides via domestic violence in #JerseyCity. We’ll continue to put serious investment here and we will innovate with programs to help. 

Under our administration, we’re the only municipality in NJ that offers a free domestic violence program for offenders via our muni court. 

It’s is called the Peaceful Families program. It is 27 weeks long program and a very intensive class. About 90% of all defendants are required to participate as a prerequisite to disposition of their case.  We offer that class to both men and women. We offer English and Spanish and we are working on more languages and more classes- LBGTQ, etc. 

Furthermore, if the defendant needs additional services, such as substance abuse counseling, the program assists with that referral. 

Many of the dv defendants have mental health issues as well. So, those defendants get transferred to mental health court and we offer both dv counseling and mental health services- such as medication management, psychiatric evaluations, counseling, etc. 

We also work with Women Rising. The prosecutor refers all victims to their liaison. They offer counseling for victims, relocation, temporary shelter, job training, 

So as a city, we try to assist both sides- both the defender and the victim. Quite a few defendants also stay in the class beyond the 27 weeks. They find the opportunity to engage in therapy sessions/peer groups helpful. 

Hope that provides some context on the JC side as we are proactive + we need to continue to support victims here w/meaningful help. 

Most important please think about the victims and their families and education around the services to help - finally, and most important please consider supporting the scholarship fund for the children of Miss Hernandez who sadly lost her life this week

From my time serving as a U.S. Marine to leading Jersey City as Mayor, my career has always been guided by a strong desire to take on difficult challenges and find solutions that help improve peoples’ lives. Now I’m running for Governor to bring those same values to Trenton.

I believe that New Jersey can become an even better place for all of us, and over the coming months, I’ll be sharing my vision for how we’ll make it happen. I’ve never backed down from a fight before, and I’m ready to work hard for all the people of our great state to deliver the results New Jersey deserves. Join me at the link in my bio.

For anyone that dealt with Jersey City over the last 30 years, they would have encountered Robert Byrne and every single one of them would have left with a positive and memorable experience. For me, I have countless examples as he embraced me when I was an outside councilman first elected and taught me about government, he was the master of ceremonies when I was first elected mayor of Jersey City, he was a self designated counsel in my personal life as he lectured me countless times about the importance of family over politics, and he officiated my wedding at City Hall with Jaclyn. The most amazing thing is how close I felt to Robert is the same way thousands of people felt about him in Jersey City. His passing is a massive loss to Jersey City as he embodied everything that was special about the old born and raised Jersey City in that he loved Jersey City more than one could convey. Robert’s legacy will be remembered here forever, and in a place that prides itself on historical bigger than life government officials, Robert will join the ranks of the most significant in Jersey City history.  We will fly the flags next week at half staff to honor him  and our prayers are with the Byrne family during these difficult times

This week we will present to the Council a Professional Services Agreement with Planned Parenthood to Expand our Successful Pilot Partnerships to increase Women’s Health

 In 2022, we kicked off the pilot program in which the WIC of Jersey City and Planned Parenthood(PPMNJ) have formulated the first of its kind Partnership between the two agencies.  As Planned Parenthood is a natural extension of the mission of the Jersey City WIC program, as it embodies the much needed reproductive support of the participants.  Never have these services been more crucial to the needs of the population that they service. 
 
During the first ten months of the pilot program, this partnership has serviced more than 20% of Jersey City WIC’s eligible (adult female) cliental. 

As encouraging as these numbers are, they don’t even begin to quantify the true scope of this Partnership.  The more than 20% (21.4%) of the individuals that received these services were also referred to other community partners including Medicaid, which aided in affordable service which they might have otherwise been unable to receive. 
 
Some of the additional services they received were: general checkups, emergency visits, birth control and pap smears.  Again, these are all services that they may not have had access to without the Partnership.

This also is incredibly impactful in terms of preventative health. With all of the participants being on or below the poverty line, this essential service cannot be overlooked with the current cost of owning and maintaining a vehicle.  This could potentially be the difference between these participants being able to receive medical care.
 
This type of Partnership serves as a prime example of two organizations working together to expand their scope of services and expanding the reach of resources to their cliental. 

At the next council meeting we will be doubling the investment here.  We are about action in JC.

On Monday we will share our Steven Fulop For Governor Transportation Plan for NJ. My goal is to be more clear than any gubernatorial candidate in NJ history on what my priorities will be/what I will change when elected. I think you as a resident deserve a clear agenda and not just the big rhetoric that most campaigns provide. 

Anyone who knows my engagement in Jersey City over the years knows I’m involved with details. In 2013, as a candidate, I set a clear plan for what I wanted to do here in Jersey City on each front and then when elected we executed on it. Since we started sharing plans, I have been elected 3 times by huge numbers which speaks to support. In Trenton, it won’t be learning on the job bc I have lived the challenges for 10 years here + I think have familiarity on strengths/weaknesses for where/how Trenton interacts with us. 

Going forward our goal is to release a different detailed campaign plan, on different topics, appropriately one per month over the next year
Holy Rosary La Festa Italiano - 120 Years in #JerseyCity

Climate change has been a focus of our administration over the last 10 years. We have taken important and inclusive actions focusing on mitigating climate change, increasing resiliency, investing in a green economy, and ensuring equity across Jersey City’s communities. 

We have been steadfast through significant investment in policies and initiatives for climate action.

Since pioneering a resolution to fight climate change in 2015, Jersey City has been aggressive and progressive in addressing our environment’s worst health offenders by building a robust bicycle and pedestrian infrastructure, launching the City’s first microtransit system, switching our municipal fleet to fully electric vehicles (including the first electric garbage trucks on the entire East Coast), becoming the first in the state of New Jersey to ban plastic bags, and advancing other important initiatives to tackle the environmental realities of the 21st century. We joined the “Mayors for Climate” Coalition in 2017 following President Trump’s withdrawal from the Paris Climate Agreement, under which he have maintained a commitment to increase investments in renewable energy and energy efficiency. In 2021, Jersey City developed a Climate and Energy Action Plan (CEAP) to create a strategic framework for reducing greenhouse gas emissions and responding to the impacts that climate change will have on Jersey City. Since then, the City has invested in a multi-million dollar Energy Savings Improvement Program to improve energy efficiency at 28 municipal facilities with lighting upgrades, solar panel installations, and other strategies that will reduce operational costs and yield long term energy savings for the residents of the City.

I’m the mayor of the most diverse city in the country per capita. My dad fought in the IDF + my family is Holocaust survivors w/28 out of 35 of my family murdered in the gas chambers. I also mentored a Palestinian young man since high school + who I also I appointed to a vacant city council seat even though the district he represents is not predominantly Muslim nor Palestinian. He is a great human being and I i knew he would do a good job is why I did it. Also important point for my history, the Muslim community here was the first community to support me politically as councilman/mayor and frankly I wouldn’t be the mayor without them. 

So this leads me to what we see around us nationally and i truthfully never thought I would see the amount of anti-semitism we are seeing since the Holocaust nor the return of this amount of Islamophobia that we saw firsthand after 9/11 - both are happening.  I see rallies in Jersey City over the next few days and we always encourage people here to express their views but I hope we can keep perspective that our neighbors here are BOTH Jewish and Muslim and our words/actions at these rallies matter - many people watch and are scared.

I know we will keep Jersey City as a shining example of a place that all are welcome and feel safe . You may not be able to control peace in the Middle East directly but you can directly keep neighbors feeling that this community is one which values them.

I personally I have some influence over what happens here in Jersey City and I try to lead by example. I have, and always will, run a city based on inclusion and safety and prosperity. It is sad what we see nationally and Right now, more than ever, we need leaders, clergy, politicians and all people attending these rallies to come together and respect each other regardless of race and religion and turn back the rhetoric of hate/anger that is happening at these demonstrations. Let’s be mindful of what we say/do and try our best to be thoughtful to express our views in a peaceful way that doesn’t alienate and attack our neighbors.

My statement on Menendez: Late last week, the Hudson County Democratic Organization issued a statement that they would support Congressman Rob Menendez for another term in office.I respect the position of the mayors in Hudson County and we have a close relationship but I have a different view here. 

I’m not on board with supporting Rob Menendez for another term in Congress. It’s time to move on.

When the Senator first got indicted, I thought maybe I could separate the father and son, and I even expressed that to Rob. As time went on, I realized it is impossible to do that and the situations are tied together. It’s not a secret that Rob got to Congress only because of his dad's influence, so it’s fair to move on from Rob now because of that same influence.

It is also clear that the Senator continues to say he will still run for reelection despite the embarrassment for our state, the Senator still threatens people privately and publicly, and the congressman has not separated himself from any of it. I understand it’s his dad, but it’s unreasonable to be linked together because of family only when it helps.

The voters will ultimately decide what they want. I believe a clean slate is needed and is best for both Hudson County and New Jersey. (Photo cred: NJ Monitor)
